Maps: Exercises

Exercises

These exercises accompany the Maps tutorial.

Use the following code to download 2014 daily No2 data for the United States. This data will be used in the excercises.

# create a temporary file
temp <- tempfile()

# download the .zip file to a temporary file--this might take a minute or two
download.file('http://aqsdr1.epa.gov/aqsweb/aqstmp/airdata/daily_42602_2014.zip', temp)

# unzip temporary file to your working directory
unzip(temp)

# delete the temporary file
unlink(temp)

# read the data into R
no2 <- read.csv('daily_42602_2014.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  1. Use dplyr to summarize the no2 data frame so that each monitor has one record with a column for the NO2 mean for the entire year and a column for the standard deviation.

Solution

  1. Use the data frame created in the first exercise to create a map of the monitors (use map() and points()).

Solution

  1. Use the data frame created in the first exercise and subset it down to monitors in Ohio. Plot those monitors on a map and label them with the “City.Name” column.

Solution

  1. Use choroplethr to make a heat map of the number of NO2 monitors in each state.

Solution

  1. Use googleVis to make a Google map of the Ohio monitors.

Solution

  1. Use leaflet to make a Leaflet map of the Ohio monitors.

# filter out days with less than 75% valid hours
no2 <- filter(no2, Observation.Percent >= 75)
no2_annual <- group_by(no2, State.Code, County.Code, Site.Num, 
                    Latitude, Longitude, Datum, State.Name, 
                    County.Name, City.Name, CBSA.Name)
no2_annual <- summarize(no2_annual, no2_mean = mean(Arithmetic.Mean, na.rm = TRUE),
                        no2_sd = sd(Arithmetic.Mean, na.rm = TRUE))
as.tbl(no2_annual)

Solution 2

library(maps)
map(database = 'usa')
points(x = no2_annual$Longitude, y = no2_annual$Latitude,pch = 19)

Back to exercises

Solution 3

ohio <- filter(no2_annual, State.Name == "Ohio")
map(database = 'state', regions = "ohio")
points(x = ohio$Longitude, y = ohio$Latitude,pch = 19)
title(main = "Ohio NO2 Monitor Locations")
text(x = ohio$Longitude, y = ohio$Latitude, labels = ohio$City.Name, pos = 4)

Back to exercises

Solution 4

Make a summary table of the number of NO2 monitors in each state.

monitors <- group_by(no2_annual, State.Name)
monitors <- summarize(monitors, value = n())

Make a column named “region” that is all lowercase state names and has a character class. Remove non-states.

monitors$region <- as.character(tolower(monitors$State.Name))
monitors <- filter(monitors, region != "puerto rico")

Plot.

library(choroplethr)
no2_map <- state_choropleth(monitors[, c("region", "value")],
                                  legend = "NO2 Monitors")
no2_map

Solution 5

library(googleVis)
ohio$google.location <- paste(ohio$Latitude, ohio$Longitude, sep = ":")
# here I create a more informative label
ohio$label <- paste("NO2 Annual Mean:", round(ohio$no2_mean, 3))
g.inter.map <- gvisMap(data = ohio, locationvar = "google.location",
                       tipvar = "label")
plot(g.inter.map)

Solution 6

library(leaflet)
m <- leaflet()
m <- addTiles(m)
m <- addMarkers(m, lng=ohio$Longitude, lat=ohio$Latitude, 
                popup=ohio$label)
